                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d553">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/129</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chinese Chargé (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_YH2" type="to"
                            >Yen</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The Secretary of State presents his compliments to the Chargé d’Affaires ad
                    interim of China and acknowledges with thanks the receipt of his note of June 4,
                        1932,<note n="62" xml:id="d553fn62">Not printed.</note> stating that a
                    cablegram was received on that day from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in
                    Nanking to the effect that <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Captain
                        Charles Baker</persName> had been released. The Department of State is
                    gratified at the safe release of this American <pb facs="0617" n="519"
                        xml:id="pg_519"/> citizen and is appreciative of efforts to that end put
                    forth by the Chinese Government and its agencies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-10">June 10,
                            1932</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
